To demonstrate that the one-dimensional wave equation is satisfied by the function \( y = A\sqrt{x + vt} \), we need to consider the standard form of the one-dimensional wave equation and substitute the given function into it. Here is the properly formatted LaTeX code for this task:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Verification of the Wave Equation}

The one-dimensional wave equation is given by:
\begin{equation}
    \frac{\partial^2 y}{\partial t^2} = v^2 \frac{\partial^2 y}{\partial x^2}
\end{equation}

We need to show that this equation is satisfied by the function:
\begin{equation}
    y = A\sqrt{x + vt}
\end{equation}

First, compute the first partial derivatives:
\begin{align}
    \frac{\partial y}{\partial x} &= \frac{A}{2\sqrt{x + vt}} \\
    \frac{\partial y}{\partial t} &= \frac{Av}{2\sqrt{x + vt}}
\end{align}

Next, compute the second partial derivatives:
\begin{align}
    \frac{\partial^2 y}{\partial x^2} &= -\frac{A}{4(x + vt)^{3/2}} \\
    \frac{\partial^2 y}{\partial t^2} &= -\frac{Av^2}{4(x + vt)^{3/2}}
\end{align}

Substitute these into the wave equation:
\begin{equation}
    -\frac{Av^2}{4(x + vt)^{3/2}} = v^2 \left(-\frac{A}{4(x + vt)^{3/2}}\right)
\end{equation}

Both sides of the equation are equal, thus confirming that the function \( y = A\sqrt{x + vt} \) satisfies the one-dimensional wave equation.

\end{document}
```

This LaTeX document outlines the steps to verify that the given function satisfies the one-dimensional wave equation by calculating the necessary partial derivatives and substituting them into the wave equation.

